Au clair de la lune ...🌝
•Follow @encorefrenchlessons and level up your Frenchness
.
TRADUCTION LITTÉRALE
Être dans la lune: to be in the moon
Demander la lune: to ask for the moon
Décrocher la lune: to unhook the moon
Être mal luné: to be bad mooned
Une lune de miel: a moon of honey
.
NOTE
Quand il s'agit réellement du satellite naturel de la Terre, on met une majuscule à « Lune »
.
.

J'ai fort envie de frites belges !🍟
•Follow @EncoreFrenchLessons and level up your frenchness
.
VOCABULAIRE
La Belgique: Belgium
Belge: belgian
.
FUN FACT
The choice of the Gallic rooster as a symbol for France dates back to the collapse of the Roman Empire and the formation of Gaul. It finds its origin in a play on word on gallus (Latin for rooster) and Gallus (Gallic). Despite its frequent use as a symbol for France, in particular by sports federations, the rooster has never been an official emblem. “Cocorico !” (French for “cock-a-doodle-doo”) is often used as an affirmation of French patriotism.
.
The Belgian Lion (Leo Belgicus), a yellow lion with red claws and tongue, on a black background. It is notably represented on the small seal of the State. It symbolizes the seventeen Provinces of the former Netherlands.
.
.
.
.
.
.

Measure your Frenchness🥖->🚬
•Follow @encorefrenchlessons and level up your Frenchness
.
Dropping the "e" between two consonnants is pretty frequent in spoken French
.
NOTE
There is no perfect translation from English to French to "à ce qu'il paraît"
Literally: to what it appears
Paraître: to seem, to appear
Apparement: apparently
.
EXEMPLES
À ce qu'il paraît on pourra bientôt bientôt voyager en France comme avant
They say that soon we will be able to travel in France as before
.
À ce qu'il paraît ils vont se marier
I've heard they are getting married
.
